# Python API & Bot

## API Layout (`packages/api/app/`)

- `main.py` — FastAPI app, CORS, router mounts
- `auth/telegram.py` — initData HMAC validation
- `auth/session.py` — session token create/resolve/prune (v2.0)
- `routes/` — auth, runs, leaderboard (thin handlers)
- `routes/_users.py` — user upsert helper (shared by auth + runs)
- `routes/_cooldowns.py` — Supabase submit cooldown (v2.0)
- `routes/_plausibility.py` — score plausibility + sprint_mode validation (v2.0)
- `db/supabase.py` — Supabase client singleton
- `models.py` — Pydantic request/response models

## Conventions

- Validate Telegram `initData` on every authenticated endpoint (`/auth/me`, `/runs`).
- Score sanity checks: years 0–100, rungs ≈ years × 4, plausibility cap, `sprint_mode` vs daily preset.
- `GET /leaderboard` — public list, no initData.
- `POST /leaderboard/me` — `session_token` marks current user row (v2.0).
- Rate limit: Supabase `submit_cooldowns` primary (migration 002); in-memory fallback in `runs.py` for tests/dev.
- All DB writes use service role key; never expose to client.
- Use pydantic models for request/response; no raw dicts in route signatures.
- Bot (`apps/bot/`): `/start`, `/go`, `/play`, `/help`; private chat → `web_app` button; groups → `t.me/bot?startapp` URL button.

## Testing

```bash
cd packages/api && pip install -r requirements.txt && pytest
```

## Deploy

Railway Dockerfile in `packages/api/`. Health check: `GET /health`. Run Supabase migration `002_v2_hardening.sql` before v2.0 sign-off.
